column168: THE DRIVER TOOK THE CAP OFF OF THE VAPOR RECOVERY OF THE TRUCK.  ONCE IT WAS OPENED ABOUT 2 GALLONS SPILLED OUT ONTO THE GROUND.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED & CLEANED UP TO SUPERVISOR SATISFACTION.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: AT THE BEGINNING OF THE UNLOAD PROCESS AIR PRESSURE WAS APPLIED TO CARGO TANK.  THERE DEVELOPED A CRACK IN A WELD IN VALVE - PROCESS STOPPED AND LOAD WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  TANK WAS OFFLOADED AND VALVING CLEANED AND REPAIRED.

GAUGE ON CUSTOMER'S (CONSIGNEE) INDICATED THERE WAS ENOUGH SPACE IN THE STORAGE TANK TO HOLD ALL THE PRODUCT (44,640LBS). CUSTOMER HOOKED UP THEIR HOSE TO THE TRAILER AND HAD DRIVER CONNECT AIR HOSE FOR PRESSURE UNLOADING. HAD BEEN UNLOADING FOR APPROXIMATELY 20-30 MINUTES WHEN OPERATOR TOLD DRIVER THEIR STORAGE TANK WAS OVERFLOWING. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE VALVES ON THE TRAILER AND STOPPED THE UNLOADING PROCESS. CUSTOMER CLEANED UP SPILL AND EXCESS PORTION OF PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER AS THEY HAD NO OTHER TANK TO COMPLETE UNLOADING. GAUGE ON STORAGE TANK APPARENTLY DEFECTIVE AND NOT REGISTERING THE CORRECT AMOUNT OF PRODUCT IN THEIR STORAGE TANK. REPLACING THE GAUGE SHOULD CORRECT ANY FUTURE PROBLEMS.
DRIVER WAS PUMPING OFF DIESEL FUEL ON PASSENGER SIDE OF TRUCK. VALVE FAILED ON DRIVERS SIDE SPRAYING APX 50 GALLONS ONTO PAYED DRIVEWAY.

column168: DURING YARD SWITCHING OPERATIONS, TANK CAR GATX 26217 DERAILED.  THE TANK CAR FELL TO ITS RIGHT SIDE DURING THE DERAILMENT AND STRUCK A COVERED HOPPER CAR ON THE ADJACENT TRACK.  THE COLLISION WITH THE HOPPER CAR RESULTED IN DAMAGE TO THE VALVES AND MANWAY COVER OF THE TANK CAR.  THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER WAS TORN LOOSE OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING NOZZLE; THIS EXPOSED THE LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE, VAPOR EDUCTION PIPE, AND VACUUM RELIEF DEVICE.  THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE WAS DISLODGED FROM THE LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED THROUGH THE PIPE.  THE AIR LINE VALVE WAS DISLODGED FROM THE AIR LINE PIPE FLANGE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED FROM THE PIPE.  THE VACUUM RELIEF DEVICE COVER WAS STRUCK CAUSING THE VALVE STEM TO BE BENT, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE THROUGH THE VALVE.  THE MANWAY COVER LID WAS ALSO STRUCK.  THE BOLT AT THE 3 O'CLOCK POSITION WAS SHEARED OFF ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE THROUGH THE MANWAY. THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE (PRV) ON THE B END OF THE CAR WAS ALSO IMPACTED. DURING THE IMPACT, 2 OF THE 4 RETAINING BOLTS WERE SHEARED OFF, THIS RELEASED TENSION ON THE PRV SPRING ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE THROUGH THE PRV.  THE LEAKING FLANGES WERE PLUGGED AND THE MANWAY COVER WAS TIGHTENED TO REDUCE THE AMOUNT OF LEAKAGE.  CONTAINMENT POOLS WERE PLACED BELOW THE LEAKING VALVES AND APPLIANCES UNTIL THE CAR WAS UP RIGHTED.  WHEN THE CAR WAS UP RIGHTED, ALL OF THE LEAKAGE STOPPED.  THE CAR WAS THEN MOVED TO AN ISOLATED TRACK.  THE CONTENTS OF THE DAMAGED TANK CAR WERE TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER TANK CAR (UTLX 48583).  THE RAIL BALLAST AND SOIL ADJACENT TO THE CAR THAT WAS IMPACTED BY THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS EXCAVATED AND WILL BE DISPOSED OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH APPLICABLE REGULATIONS.

THE GENERAL CAR FORMAN AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN COLUMBUS, OH REPORTED THAT A SWITCH CREW OBSERVED WETNESS ON THE SIDE OF GATX300411, A LOAD OF COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID NOS.  THE CAR WAS PLACED IN AN ISOLATED TRACK. THE SHIPPER, LUBRIZOL CORP, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  LUBRIZOL CONTRACTED RESCAR TO MAKE REPAIRS TO THE CAR.  THE RESCAR REPRESENTATIVE REPORTED THAT THE SECUREMENT BOLTS ON 2 BLIND FLANGES ON TOP OF THE CAR WERE LESS THAN FINGER TIGHT.  THE BOLTS WERE MADE WRENCH TIGHT.  RESCAR ALSO CHECKED THE MANWAY COVER; IT WAS PROPERLY SECURED.  HE ALSO CHECKED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET AND IT WAS OK.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION. CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT REPORTED THESE FINDINGS TO THE SHIPPER.  THE SHIPPER WILL INVESTIGATE AND FOLLOW-UP FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

column168: AT 0820 HOURS ON NOVEMBER 3, 2002 A CSXT CAR DEPARTMENT EMPLOYEE FOUND TANK CAR UTLX12491 LEAKING FROM AROUND THE BOTTOM CENTER OF THE RAIL CAR.  CSX MANAGERS IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED THEIR TRANSPORTATION EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.  ALL LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.  HEPACO ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS NOTED THAT THE RELEASE WAS ORIGINATING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CLOSURE (BLIND) FLANGE GASKET.  APPROXIMATELY FIFTY (50) GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ONTO THE ASPHALT/CONCRETE SURFACE AND ABSORBED WITH SAND TO PREVENT MIGRATION.  A RESIDUE CAR WAS LOCATED IN THE YARD, GATX73674. HEPACO TRANSFERRED THE PHOSPHORIC ACID INTO THE RESIDUE CAR.

RCRX1309, RESIDUE, LAST CONTAINED HYDROCHLORIC ACID, WAS DISCOVERED VENTING VAPORS FROM THE TOP AT CSX TRANSPORTATIONS YEOMAN YARD, TAMPA, FL.  THE TRAINMASTER NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER DIRECTLY.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT CALLED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO REPAIR THE LEAK AND NOTIFIED CHEMTREC.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT ALL BOLTS ON THE LIQUID LINE'S BLIND FLANGE WERE LESS THAN FINGER TIGHT ALLOWING VAPORS TO ESCAPE.  THEY SECURED THE FLANGE BOLTS WRENCH TIGHT AND THE VAPOR RELEASE STOPPED.  THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT SPOKE TO DAVID RIVERS, BRENNTAG MID SOUTH, AND ADVISED HIM OF THE PROBLEM FOUND WITH THE CAR.  HE WILL FOLLOW-UP WITH THE CLEARWATER PLANT PERSONNEL.
NO REMARKS

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING AT THE INTERSECTION OF INTERSTATE 59 AND INTERSTATE 12 THE SLAY TRANSPORTATION CO., INC. VEHICLE OVERTURNED.  AS A RESULT, APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WERE RELEASED FROM THE VENT CAP OF THE CARGO TANKER. CLEAN UP WAS PERFORMED BY GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. OF NEW ORLEANS, LOUISIANA.  GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. TRANSFERRED THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE OVERTURNED TANKER INTO ANOTHER TANKER.  GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. USED ABSORBENT PADS TO ABSORB THE FREE PRODUCT.  THE ABSORBENT PADS WERE PLACED INTO TWO (2) FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.  GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. REMOVED IMPACTED SOIL FROM THE AFFECTED AREA.  THE IMPACTED SOIL WAS PLACED INTO A ROLL OFF BOX FOR DISPOSAL.  GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE GENERATED DURING THE CLEAN UP.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.  ALL FEDERAL, STATE, LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

SINCE GUIDEBOOK NUMBER SUGGESTED TO REMOVE PEOPLE UP TO 60 FEET AWAY, TROOPER GOSSETT CHOSE TO CLOSE SCALES AND WOULD NOT ALLOW DRIVER TO HIS TRUCK TO PLACE A BUCKET UNDER THE DRIP TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  MATERIAL WAS K071, THUS IT HAD A ONE POUND RQ.  FIELD SERVICE EMPLOYEES WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE, WHERE THEY ASSESSED THE AREA, CONTAINED THE MATERIAL (<1 SQUARE FOOT AND ONE PINT).  CAULKING WAS USED TO SEAL THE HOLES IN THE TRAILER, AND AREA WAS CLEANED.  THE DOT THEN ALLOWED THE TRAILER TO RETURN TO CALVERT CITY.  SMALL HOLE MUST HAVE BEEN MADE IN TRAILER DURING LAST USE THAT WAS UNDETECTED DURING LOADING. LIQUIDS TRAPPED IN MATERIAL SETTLED OUT DURING TRANSPORTATION.  SOME COST MAY BE ASSOCIATED WITH IL.  SCALES. (LINE 23 E)

column168: CUSTOMER LOADED TRAILER AND ADVISED DRIVER TO GO TO SCALES AND WEIGH TO MAKE SURE THERE WAS ADEQUATE VOLUME ON THE UNIT, AS THE DRIVER PULLED UP GRADE TO THE SCALES A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SEEPED OUT AROUND THE DOME LID GASKET. TRAILER WAS UNLOADED AND SENT TO THE TERMINAL FOR REPAIR AND A RELIEF UNIT SENT IN. AT THE TERMINAL IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE DOME GASKET WAS A ROPE TEFLON GASKET WHICH HAS A TENDENCY TO LEAK IF THE DOME LID IS NOT PROPERLY SECURED, NOT OTHER PROBLEMS WERE NOTICED. THE DRIVER WAS NOT ALLOWED ON THE TANK AT THE CUSTOMER FACILITY AND DID NOT PHYSICALLY DO THE LOADING. THE SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT THAT LEAKED EVAPORATED QUICKLY. UNITS BEING SENT TO THIS FACILITY FOR LOADING ARE TO BE PREPPED PRIOR TO DISPATCH TO MAKE SURE UNIT HAS PROPER GASKET AND THAT THE DOME LID WILL SECURE PROPERLY.

PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, ABSORBENTS, ABSORBENT WIPES, AND ACETONE. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PATCHED WITH PUTTY AND ACCEPTED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT BY THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, TWO LEAKING FIFTY POUND PLASTIC BAGS WERE DISCOVERED ON A SHRINKWRAPPED SKID AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY THREE POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A FORKLIFT PUNCTURE TO THE BAGS. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, DUSTPANS, AND A BROOM. THE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTEEN GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND AFFECTED SHRINKWRAP WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TEN GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM. BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE TWO LEAKING BAGS WERE REPAIRED WITH TAPE, AND THEY WERE FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING, FOUR, ONE GALLON METAL CANS WAS DISCOVERED AT THE HALF MARK OF THE TRAILER. UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT TWO CANS WERE DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING TWO CANS WERE AFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE DAMAGE TO THE CANS WAS DUE TO BEING CRUSHED BY HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND TWO DAMAGED CANS WERE PLACED INTO, ONE TWENTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM AND ONE, SEVEN GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. BOTH DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE TWO AFFECTED CANS WERE CLEANED, RECOUPED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

DURING ROUTINE INSPECTION OF IRBY YARD IN LAURENS, SOUTH CAROLINA, CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MANAGER HOPES FOUND TANK CAR NLTX5022 RELEASING VAPOR OF ACETATE.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALS THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE TO BE A DEFECTIVE (BROKEN) VACUUM RELIEF VALVE SPRING. LOSS OF PRODUCT / VAPORS ESTIMATED AT LESS THAN 1/2 GALLON.  SHIPPER MADE REPAIRS.

A TRAINMASTER AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN MONTGOMERY, AL, REPORTED THAT A SWITCH CREW OBSERVED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR NATX29772 A LOAD OF ACETONE.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED. THE SHIPPER, GENERAL ELECTRIC WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.   MICKY COTHRAN WITH GE PLASTICS, THE CONSIGNEE, RESPONDED TO MAKE REPAIRS.  MR. COTHRAN REPORTED THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE WHERE THE VALVE SCREWED INTO THE TOP OF THE CAR. THE PRESSURE IN THE CAR WAS INCREASED TO PIN POINT THE EXACT LEAK LOCATION.  THE PRODUCT EVAPORATED BEFORE REACHING THE GROUND. COTHRAN TIGHTENED THE LIQUID VALVE.  THE LEAK STOPPED.  COTHRAN INDICATED HE WOULD ADVISE THE ORIGIN PLANT OF THE LEAK & HAVE THEM INSPECT OTHER CARS FOR SIMILAR PROBLEMS.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1900 HOURS ON NOVEMBER 27, 2002 CSX TRANSPORTATION YARD CREW Y205-27 WAS SWITCHING CARS IN BENNETT YARD.  HOPPER CAR CNLX5256 (AAR CAR TYPE C113) AND TANK CAR UTLX647370 ROLLED OUT OF TRACK 15 AND WAS STRUCK BY CARS BEING PULLED OUT OF TRACK 13.  AFTER A THROUGH INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAUSE OF THE DERAILMENT WAS HUMAN FACTOR.  AS A RESULT OF THE COLLISION, HOPPER CAR CNLX5256 DERAILED WHEELS #1 AND #2. THE COLLISION ALSO CAUSED A 4" BY 1/2" TEAR ON THE "BR" SIDE OF THE CAR APPROXIMATELY NINE (9) FEET ABOVE THE GROUND.  THIS TEAR RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF 50 POUNDS OF FERTILIZER GRADE AMMONIUM NITRATE.  SWS ENVIRONMENTAL PLACED A TEMPORARY PATCH TO CONFINE THE PRODUCT INSIDE THE CONTAINER.  CSX TRANSPORTATION MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT WILL ARRANGE WITH THE SHIPPER TO MAKE PERMANENT REPAIRS.  THE TRAIN CREW WILL RECEIVE DISCIPLINE ACCORDING TO COMPANY POLICY.  BENNETT YARD MANAGEMENT WILL USE THIS INCIDENT AS A KEY FOCUS AREA FOR JOB SAFETY BRIEFINGS HELD DURING THE WEEK OF DECEMBER 2ND.

column168: SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF DRUM ON NON-STANDARD PALLETS.  THERE WERE THREE DRUMS PER PALLET EXCEPT THAT ONE PALLET HAD FOUR DRUMS ON IT.  THE DRUMS ON THAT PALLET OVERHUNG THE CORNERS OF THE PALLET.  THEY WERE HELD TOGETHER WITH A SINGLE TURN OF SHRINK WRAP.  A DOCK EMPLOYEE AT THE CARRIER'S FACILITY WAS USING A FORK LIFT TO UNLOAD THE INBOUND PICK UP TRAILER.  AS HE EXITED THE TRAILER, THE SHRINK WRAP FAILED.  ONE DRUM FELL FROM THE PALLET AND STRUCK A STEEL COLUMN ON THE DOCK.  THE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED AT A POINT ABOUT THREE INCHES FROM THE TOP.  DOCK PERSONNEL PUT THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE AND SECURED IT TO A PALLET, PREVENTING ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE.  THEY PUT OIL DRY ONTO THE SPILL AND CONTACTED THE CARRIER'S HAZMAT SPECIALIST.  AFTER CONSIDERABLE DELAY DUE TO AN INCORRECT EMERGENCY RESPONSE PHONE NUMBER AND UNCERTAINTY OVER THE CORRECT IDENTITY OF THE SHIPPER, THE SPECIALIST ESTABLISHED CONTACT WITH A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE SHIPPER.  THE REPRESENTATIVE STATED THAT IT WOULD BE ACCEPTABLE TO PLUG THE HOLE WITH PIG PUTTY, THEN OVERPACK THE DRUM.  THE SHIPPER PROVIDED AN AUTHORIZATION TO RETURN THE MATERIAL TO THEM.  NOTE: THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER THAT HAD BEEN ON THE SHIPPER'S DOCUMENT WAS (800) 228-5635, EXT. 150.  IT IS A POISON CONTROL AND MEDICAL INFORMATION CENTER.  THEY AT FIRST DID NOT RECOGNIZE THE NAME OF THE SHIPPER AS A CLIENT.  THEY LATER DETERMINED THAT THE SHIPPER HAD BEEN A CLIENT AT SOME TIME IN THE PAST, BUT HAD NOT BEEN FOR SEVERAL YEARS.  WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF CHEMTREC, THE CORRECT NAME OF THE SHIPPER WAS DETERMINED AND RECOGNIZED AS A CHEMTREC CLIENT.  CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER WAS ESTABLISHED THROUGH CHEMTREC.

CARRIER'S VEHICLE WAS PROCEEDING NORTHBOUND ON I-95 IN THE VICINITY OF EXIT 29, NEAR LEXINGTON, MASS.  DRIVER STATES THAT AS HE WAS PASSING A SERVICE AREA AN AUTO EXITED THE SERVICE PLAZA AND CROSSED SEVERAL LANES OF TRAFFIC. IN ORDER TO AVOID A COLLISION IT WAS NECESSARY FOR THE CARRIER'S DRIVER TO MAKE A PANIC STOP.  HE THEN MOVED HIS VEHICLE TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD AND STOPPED TO INSPECT THE LOAD.  WHEN HE DID, HE SAW LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  HE IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST.  THE SPECIALIST ADVISED THE DRIVER TO OBSERVE WHERE THE LIQUID MIGHT GO AND TO PUT MATERIALS FROM HIS SPILL KIT DOWN IN ATTEMPT TO CONTROL THE FLOW.  AFTER DOING SO, THE DRIVER REPORTED THAT THE SPILLAGE APPEARED TO BE CONTAINED.  THE DRIVER THEN OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR.  HE REPORTED THAT THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED FORWARD BREAKING A LOGISITC BAR.  SEVERAL DRUMS OF MATERIAL WERE DAMAGED.  ONE DRUM HAD BROKEN OPEN AND APPEARED TO BE EMPTY. HE TENTATIVELY IDENTIFIED IT AS A HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION.  AT THAT POINT THE SPECIALIST RETAINED THE SERVICES OF A CONTRACTOR TO PROCEED TO THE SITE TO HANDLE MITIGATION OF THE INCIDENT.  THE SPECIALIST ALSO NOTIFIED THE MASSACHUSETTS DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION.  THEY, IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE LEXINGTON, MASS. FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE MASSACHUSETTS STATE POLICE.  UPON ARRIVAL OF THE STATE POLICE, THEY CLOSED THE ROAD.  DUE TO THE CLOSURE OF A MAJOR HIGHWAY (I-95/MASS. 128) THE CONTRACTOR, ACTING ON BEHALF OF THE CARRIER, NOTIFIED THE U.S. COAST GUARD NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  THE CARRIER WAS ASKED TO PROVIDE ANOTHER TRAILER TO TRANSFER THE FREIGHT INTO.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT INCIDENT COMMANDER WOULD NOT ALLOW THE CARRIER'S CONTRACTOR TO BEGIN WORK UNTIL IT WAS ON SITE. ONCE IT WAS THERE, TASK OF TRANSFERRING UNDAMAGED PACKAGES AND ISOLATING DAMAGE PACKAGES WAS BEGUN.  THE DAMAGED PACKAGES WERE PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM BY MEMBERS OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM.  IN ORDER TO DO SO, THEY LAID THE SALVAGE DRUMS AND THE DAMAGED DRUMS ONTO THEIR SIDES AND SLID THE DAMAGED DRUMS INTO THE SALVAGE DRUMS.  DURING THIS PROCESS, AN ADDITIONAL APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST.  AFTER THE DRUMS OF VARIOUS MATERIALS HAD BEEN UNLOADED FROM THE ORIGINAL TRAILER IT WAS TAKEN TO A DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC WORKS FACILITY.  THERE WERE STILL SOME BULK PACKAGES TO BE INSPECTED TO BE REMOVED.  THE TRAILER WAS ALSO TO BE DECOMTAMINATED AT THAT SITE.  THE CARRIER'S CONTRACTOR HANDLED DECONTAMINATION OF THE SITE OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: ON 11/14/02, AT APPROXIMATELY 2:40 PM EST, A GASOLINE TANKER TRUCK, OWNED AND OPERATED BY MAP, WAS MANEUVERING AROUND THE AFOREMENTIONED GASOLINE STATION PREPARING TO OFF-LOAD GASOLINE INTO THE STATION'S UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS.  THE TRANSPORT TRAILER ACCIDENTALLY STRUCK THE BARRICADE POSTS IN FRONT OF THE FUEL DISPENSING UNITS CRACKING THE TRAILER FILL TUBES CAUSING A RELEASE OF 33 GALLONS OF GASOLINE ONTO THE STATION'S FUEL LOADING AREA.  THE INITIAL 55 GALLON ESTIMATE WAS A WORSE CASE ESTIMATE AND HAS BEEN REVISED DOWNWARD AFTER FURTHER CALCULATION OF THE FILL TUBES' VOLUMES. A PICTURE OF THE DAMAGED TRAILER IS CONTAINED IN ATTACHMENT A.  THE STORES CUSTOMER SERVICE REPRESENTATIVE IMMEDIATELY DIALED 911, WHILE THE TRANSPORT DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE APPROPRIATE MAP PERSONNEL.  THE PRODUCT INITIALLY PUDDLED UNDERNEATH THE TRUCK, AND THEN BEGAN MIGRATING ACROSS THE STATIONS DRIVEWAY, TOWARDS THE STREET, AND THROUGHOUT THE FUEL LOADING AREA.  THE TRANSPORT DRIVER ASSUMED A DEFENSIVE POSTURE USING APPROXIMATELY 15 ABSORBENT PADS TO HELP CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT FROM HEADING INTO THE STREET.  APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF PRODUCT EVENTUALLY MADE IT INTO THE STREET BUT NO PRODUCT ENTERED THE STORM SEWER SYSTEM.  THE OAK PARK FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ON-SITE AND THREW DOWN TWO ABSORBENT BOOMS TO KEEP ADDITIONAL PRODUCT FROM ENTERING THE STREET.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT THEN APPLIED APPROXIMATELY FIVE GALLONS OF BIOSOLVE TO THE REMAINING SPILLED PRODUCT.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET FOR BIOSOLVE IS CONTAINED IN ATTACHMENT B.  THE CONTAMINATED AREAS WERE THEN FLUSHED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT INTO A NEARBY STORM SEWER UTILIZING APPROXIMATELY 500 GALLONS OF WATER.   THE PETROLEUM IMPACTED ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS EVENTUALLY TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE DETROIT TERMINAL FOR PRODUCT RECLAMATION AND RE-USE.  MAP'S SPILL RESPONSE TEAM BEGAN ARRIVING ON-SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 3:15 PM EST.  BY THIS TIME, THE TREATED PRODUCT HAD ALREADY BEEN FLUSHED INTO THE SEWER BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  ADDITIONALLY  AT THIS TIME, MAP PERSONNEL REQUESTED RESPONSE ASSISTANCE FROM OUR PRIMARY EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, MARINE POLLUTION CONTROL (MPC).  MAP PERSONNEL INSPECTED THE STORM SEWER AND DID NOT SEE ANY EVIDENCE OF A HYDROCARBON SHEEN.  A COMBUSTIBLE GAS MONITOR WAS ALSO USED TO TAKE  LOWER EXPLOSIVE LIMIT (LEL) READINGS IN THE MANHOLE.   THERE WAS NEVER ANY GASOLINE SMELL IN THE MANHOLE, AND MONITORING DATA NEVER EXCEEDED ZERO PERCENT LEL.   RELEASE CALCULATIONS WERE MADE AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE RELEASE VOLUME DID NOT EXCEED A REPORTABLE QUANTITY AND WAS NOT CONSIDERED A CERLA RELEASE. IT WAS ALSO MAP'S UNDERSTANDING THAT THE MICHIGAN PART 5 SPCC RULES DO NOT APPLY TO TRANSPORTATION RELATED EVENTS, SO THIS EVENT WAS NOT CONSIDERED REPORTABLE ACCORDING TO THOSE RULES.  HOWEVER, DUE TO THE CLEAN-UP TECHNIQUES EMPLOYED AND SINCE THERE WAS "POTENTIAL" FOR A SHEEN IN A NAVIGABLE WATER SYSTEM, COURTESY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO THE NRC, DEQ AND THE STATE FIRE MARSHAL.

column168: WHILE TURNING TO EXIT THE FACILITY, THE LOADED SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE TANKER SEPERATED FROM THE TRACTOR AND OVERTURNED SHEARING THE TOP FILL LINE. column168: ON NOVEMBER 18, 2003, OLIN CORP ADVISED CSX TRANSPORTATION OF A CONDITION REPORTED TO THEM BY THEIR CUSTOMER, E I DUPONT OF AMPTHILL, VA.  OVER THE COURSE OF THE PAST YEAR AND ONE HALF, DUPONT HAS DISCOVERED SMALL AMOUNTS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE RESIDUE AROUND THE BASE OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) ON 39 TANK CARS AFTER THEY HAD BEEN UNLOADED AT THE AMPTHILL, VA FACILITY.  ALL OF THE CARS ARE EQUIPPED WITH MIDLAND EXTERNAL PRD AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE TO INDICATE THE RESIDUE PRESENT WAS THE RESULT OF A PRODUCT RELEASE DURING TRANSPORTATION.  OLIN INSPECTED AND TESTED SEVERAL OF THE PRD'S AND FOUND NO MECHANICAL PROBLEMS OR DEFECTS WITH THEM.  OLIN REQUESTED CSXT'S ASSISTANCE TO REVIEW THE ROUTING AND HANDLING OF THEIR TANK CARS TRANSPORTED TO DUPONT'S  AMPTHILL, VA PLANT.  THE ROUTING INDICATED THE CARS SHIPPED FROM OLIN'S NIAGARA FALLS, NY PLANT WERE SWITCHED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARDS IN NIAGARA FALLS, NY, SELKIRK, NY, RICHMOND, VA, AND BELLWOOD, VA FOR DELIVERY TO DUPONT AT AMPTHILL.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE FROM CSXT, DUPONT OR OLIN THAT ANY OF THE CARS IN QUESTION HAD EXPERIENCED ANY UNUSUAL HANDLING OR HARD COUPLING'S IN TRANSIT.  CSXT WITH OLIN'S CORPORATION HAD INITIATED A PLAN TO EQUIP SEVERAL TANK CARS WITH IMPACT RECORDERS THAT WILL MONITOR COUPLING IMPACTS TO DETERMINE IF CAR HANDLING COULD BE A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR IN A POSSIBLE PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE PRD'S. THE STUDY WILL BEGIN THE LATTER PART OF DECEMBER AND WILL CONTINUE INTO THE FIRST QUARTER OF 2004.  EVEN THOUGH THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT THE RESIDUE DISCOVERED AROUND THE PRD'S WAS DUE TO A PRODUCT RELEASE IN TRANSIT, CSXT IS SUBMITTING THIS REPORT IN ACCORDANCE WITH SECTION 171.16 OF THE US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATIONS, 49 CFR.

column168: OUR TRANSPORT DRIVER WAS DELIVERING A LOAD OF GASOLINE TO THE GAS N SHOP LOCATED AT 1001 S 13 STREET, LINCOLN, NE, ON 11-7-02 AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 P.M.  THE SPILL OCCURRED WHEN THE TANK BECAME FULL AND GASOLINE CAME OUT OF THE REMOTE DOWNSPOUTS.  THE DRIVER, JIM MILBURN, THEN IMMEDIATELY TOOK HIS SPILL KIT OFF OF THE TRAILER AND CONTAINED THE SPILL, WHICH HE ESTIMATED AT 8 GALLONS, TO THE CEMENT DRIVEWAY AT THE LOCATION. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND SPREAD OUT 13 BAGS OF HI-DRY.  SITE RESPONSE SERVICES WERE NOTIFIED AND CLEANED UP THE DRIVE.  SITE RESPONSE SERVICE'S' JIM SMITH ESTIMATED THE SPILL AT APPROXIMATELY 8 GALLONS, AS WELL.  THE HEALTH INSPECTOR WAS ALSO ON SITE.  THE REMOTE FILLS HAVE SINCE BEEN CAPPED OFF TO PREVENT FUTURE SPILLS.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: WHILE DRIVING WESTBOUND ON THE I-90 AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30 AM, JUST WEST OF CONNEAUT, OHIO, MR. FENSTERMAKER ENCOUNTERED THREE DEER CROSSING THE ROADWAY.  HE APPLIED HIS BRAKES TO AVOID THE DEER AND THE CARGO SHIFTED, JUMPING OVER THE BLOCKS HOLDING IT IN PLACE. THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE TRAILER DID NOT FEEL RIGHT SO HE EXITED AT RT. 193, TURNING SOUTH AND PULLING INTO THE REAR OF THE SPEEDWAY SUPER AMERICA TRUCK-STOP COMPLEX INKINGSVILLE, OHIO.  THIS IS JUST SOUTH OF THE I-90 INTERCHANGE. AT THAT TIME, HE NOTICED ODOR AND SOMELIQUID RUNNING UNDER THE CARGO TRAILER.  HE THEN REPORTED THIS TO THE DISPATCHER AT OUR FIRM. INSURED OPERATOR:  OUR OFFICES INITIALLY WERE CONTACTED TO REPORT TO THE SCENE AT 10:00 AM ON THE DATE OF LOSS. WE ARRIVED AT 11:00 AM.  AT THE TIME, THERE WERE VERY HIGH WESTERLY WINDS AND THE ODOR OF THE CHEMICAL WAS NOTICED APPROXIMATELY THREE MILES EAST OF THE SPILL. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, OUR ADJUSTER MET WITH THE KINGSVILLE, OHIO FIRE DEPARTMENT CHIEF, CHIP LAUGEN.  HE ADVISED THAT THE CALL ACTUALLY CAME INTO HIS OFFICE AT 1:21 AM.  THE HAZ-MET TEAM WAS IMMEDIATELY CALLED INTO SERVICE AND YOUR OFFICES HAD INLAND WATERS OF OHIO RESPOND AS WELL. EVERYONE ARRIVED SHORTLY AFTER THE INCIDENT.  ACCORDING TO THE CHIEF, THE DRIVER REPORTED THAT THE INCIDENT OCCURRED APPROXIMATELY TWO MILES WEST OF OHIO RT 7 ON THE WESTBOUND I-90. IN AN INTERVIEW WITH YOUR DRIVER, HE ADVISED THAT HE HAD PICKED UP THE CARGO CONSISTING OF THIOGLOCOLIC ACID IN WATERLOO, NY AND WAS BOUND FOR CINCINNATI, OH. THE CARGO WAS DIVIDED INTO 15 PLASTIC  TOTES INSIDE OF METAL CAGES WITH ROOF DIMENSIONS OF 4-FT WIDE, 5-FT DEEP, 4-FT HIGH. EACH WEIGHED APPROXIMATELY 2,700 POUNDS, GIVING A TOTAL LOAD WEIGHT OF 43,497 POUNDS. ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER, THE METAL CAGES WERE SECURED BY 2X4 WOODEN PLANKS STACK TWO-HIGH, NAILED TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. THE FREIGHT LOADER, WHOSE NAME WAS UNKNOWN, ASSURED THE DRIVER THAT THE 2X4'S WOULD SECURE THE LOAD.  THE DRIVER ALSO ADDED CARGO BARS TO HELP STABILIZE THE LOAD. REMEDIATION:  AS A RESULT OF THE LOSS, YOUR FIRM NOTIFIED INLAND WATERS OF OHIO TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 AM THAT MORNING.  INLAND WATERS OF OHIO IMMEDIATELY ARRIVED TO PREVENT FURTHER CONTAMINATION. YOU'LL NOTE THAT THE SPILL WAS ON A CONCRETE AREA AND WAS NOT ABSORBED INTO THE GROUND OR WATERWAYS. IT WAS ALSO DISCOVERED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT HAD LEAKED ONTO THE I-90 WESTBOUND, BUT CLEANUP WAS NOT NECESSARY. SAND AND LIME WAS SPREAD ON RT. 193. THE DRIVEWAY OF THE TRUCK STOP WAS POWER WASHED. RT.193 SOUTHBOUND AT I-90 OVERPASS AND NORTHBOUND AT THE LAST INTERSECTION BEFORE I-90 WAS CLOSED AT APPROXIMATELY 2:00 AM AND TRAFFIC WAS RE-DIRECTED. CHIEF LAUGEN INFORMED THE EMPLOYEES AT THE TRUCK STOP THAT THEY MAY WANT TO CLOSE BECAUSE TRAFFIC WOULD NOT BE ALLOWED IN THE AREA ANYWAY.  THEY DECIDED TO STAY OPEN UNTIL 8:00 AM THAT MORNING, THEN CLOSED VOLUNTARILY. THEY WERE NOT ORDERED TO EVACUATE DUE TO HEALTH ISSUES. RT. 193 BECAME OPEN FOR TRAF
LEAKING PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO THE B A AREA AND PROCESSED THRU DMP. CLEANED AND STORED EQUIPMENT.
I RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  THE CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEETS WERE USED. A READING OF 6-9 WAS RECEIVED FROM PH TAPE.  THE EMPTY CONTAINER WAS BAGGED AND TAKEN TO THE DMP FOR DISPOSAL.

column168: FILE:2281 D, SHIPPER: PRIORITY AIRFREIGHT LTD, AWB# LON 7016384883 MLI  ON 11/12/2002 AT 0030 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BELLY #1 OF AIRCRAFT 941AX (FLIGHT #0238) AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS ELWOOD BOHL AND GARY GRAGG DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX LEAKING A BROWN LIQUID.  THIS WAS REMOVED FROM THE AREA FOR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE FIBERBOARD BOX TO CONTAIN THREE METAL RECEPTACLES WITH FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES.  THE CLOSURES WERE NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  EACH RECEPTACLE CONTAINED 1 L OF "FLAMMABLE" PAINT.   TWO OF THE THREE RECEPTACLES LEAKED 1 L OF THEIR CONTENTS.  THE AREA INVOLVED WAS WELL VENTILATED AND CLEANED WITH SOAP AND WATER BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED.  THERE WAS 1 EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  HE WAS ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO HIS WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED AND NO CHANGES WERE REPORTED WITH THESE EMPLOYEES.  NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  CLEAR OF SCENE 0051.

ICTF SECURITY, REPORTED A LEAKING CONTAINER CONTAINER, PONU 034616, LOCATED AT E5, SPACE 162. DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. INSPECTION NOTED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE RIGHT FRONT NOSE OF THE CONTAINER. A SMALL POOL, LESS THAN ONE GALLON, OF PRODUCT WAS COLLECTING ON THE PAVEMENT AREA DIRECTLY BELOW THE CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE CONTAINED AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. THE LADING CONSISTED OF EIGHTY DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED. WHILE THE BLOCKING AND BRACING APPEARED TO BE ADEQUATE, IT WAS NOT TO AAR BOE6C STANDARD. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO OFF LOAD THE DRUMS AND INSPECT FOR THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK. WHILE REMOVING THE DRUMS FROM THE TOP TIER, IT WAS NOTED THE BI-LEVEL SEPARATION CONSISTED OF FOUR FULL SHEETS OF PLYWOOD FROM THE NOSE, HOWEVER, SMALLER CUT PIECES WERE USED FOR THE LAST FOUR FEET. THE CUT PIECES OVERLAPPED IN THE CENTER, WHICH CAUSED AN UNEVEN SURFACE FOR THE TOP TIER DRUMS TO REST ON. ALSO, CARDBOARD SHEETS HAD BEEN PLACED OVER THE PLYWOOD USED FOR THE BI-LEVEL SEPARATION. THE CARDBOARD ALLOWED THE TILTED DRUMS TO SETTLE, CAUSING AN ADDITIONAL OFF SET WHERE THE DRUMS DID NOT SET EVENLY SIDE BY SIDE. A TOTAL OF 13 DRUMS WERE LOCATED THAT LEAKED DUE TO ADJACENT DRUM ABRASION TO THE BOTTOM CHIMES AND TOP ROLLING HOOPS. AN ADDITIONAL 32 DRUMS SUSTAINED DAMAGE TO WARRENT THEM UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION. THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT. ESTIMATE A TOTAL OF 65 GALLONS WAS LOST DURING TRANSIT FOR THE LEAKING DRUMS. THE SHIPPER REQUESTED THE ENTIRE LOAD BE RETURNED TO THE ORIGIN FACILITY. A SECOND CONTAINER, PONU 164758, WAS USED TO RELOAD ALL OF THE DAMAGED DRUMS, WHICH WERE ALSO PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS. THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER AND SECURED FOR MOVEMENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT 1745 HRS ON 11-08-02, CTS MGR LERCH RESPONDED TO A LEAKING TANKCAR ENTRAINED ON TRAIN QSRNL, LOCATED IN WESTFIELD TX, MILE POST 214.60 PALESTINE SUBDIVISION.  UPON ARRIVAL , MGR LERCH NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE PLUG OF THE 3 INCH BALL VALVE ON THE LIQUID LINE AND DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR, PRODUCT WAS LEAKING AT A RATE OF LESS THAN ONE GALLON AN HOUR. UPON TIGHTENING OF THE PLUG APPROXIMATELY 3/4 TURN, THE RELEASE WAS STOPPED AND CAR SECURED FROM FURTHER RELEASE. FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THE VALVE TO BE IN THE CLOSED POSITION BASED ON THE POSITION OF THE VALVE OPERATING STEM.  DUE TO THE OFFENSIVE ODOR OF THE PRODUCT, UPON SECURING OF THE CAR, MGR LERCH HAD THE CAR SET OUT IN LLOYD YARD; SPRING TEXAS FOR FURTHER HANDLING.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE RELEASE. ARRANGEMENTS WERE THEN MADE BY THE SHIPPER TO HAVE THE CAR CLEANED AND DEODORIZED BY EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL.  THE SHIPPER ALSO INDICATED AFTER THE CAR WAS OFF LOADED, THE VALVE WOULD BE INSPECTED.  AT 0040 HRS ON 11-9-02 THE CAR HAD BEEN CLEANED, DEODORIZED AND RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION, THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAYS IMPACTED, AND NO CLEAN-UP NECESSARY AS MATERIAL EVAPORATED UPON CONTACT WITH THE ATMOSPHERE.

AT 1005 HRS ON 11-9-02, MTO JIM CRABTREE REPORTED A CAR FOREMAN, COMPLAINING OF A HEADACHE AFTER DETECTING A PUNGENT ODOR IN THE AREA OF NORTH 2 TRACK, ENGLEWOOD YARD; HOUSTON, TX., HOUSTON EAST BELT SUBDIVISION, MILEPOST 7.9.  IMMEDIATE RESPONSE BY CTS MGR LERCH DEVELOPED AN ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR CELX 23269.  CAR WAS LOCATED ON THE EAST END OF NORTH TRACK 2.  INSPECTION OF CAR REVEALED TWO OF EIGHT MANWAY SWING BOLTS IN POSITION NOT WRENCH TIGHT, AND THE REMAINING SIX BOLTS LOOSE APPROXIMATELY 3/4 TO ONE TURN.  UPON TIGHTENING OF SWING BOLTS, THE CAR WAS SECURED WITH NO FURTHER RELEASE OF RESIDUE VAPOR.  THE TANKCAR WAS SUBSEQUENTLY RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. AFTER THE EMPLOYEE NOTED THE ODOR, HE WAS REMOVED FROM THE AREA AND MONITORED.  THE EMPLOYEE RESUMED NORMAL DUTIES AFTER A BRIEF PERIOD OF TIME, AND DECLINED MEDICAL ATTENTION.

MANAGER OF INTERMODAL TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED CONTAINER PONU 123366 LEAKING TWO TO THREE GALLONS OF PRODUCT ONTO ANOTHER CONTAINER AND ONTO THE CONCRETE CRANE PAD.  DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  DEVELOPED THIS CONTAINER WAS DOUBLE STACKED ON TOP OF ANOTHER CONTAINER DUE TO A CHASSIS SHORTAGE.  THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS PLACED ONTO A CHASSIS AND MOVED TO HAD MAT CONTAINMENT AREA, WHERE IT COULD BE GROUNDED.  INSPECTION NOTED THE LADING CONSISTED OF EIGHTY DRUMS, DOUBLE STACKED.  THE BLOCKING AND BRACING APPEARED TO BE ADEQUATE, HOWEVER, WAS NOT TO AAR BOE 6C STANDARD.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH THE SHIPPER TO REMOVE AND INSPECT THE DRUMS FOR DAMAGE.  WHILE REMOVING THIS DRUMS FROM THE TOP TIER IT WAS NOTED THE BI-LEVEL SEPARATION CONSISTED OF FOUR FULL SHEETS OF PLYWOOD FROM THE NOSE, AND CUT PIECES WERE USED FOR THE LAST FOUR FEET. THE CUT PIECES OVERLAPPED IN THE CENTER, CAUSING AN UNEVEN SURFACE FOR THE TOP TIER DRUMS TO REST UPON. CARDBOARD SHEETS HAD BEEN PLACED OVER THE PLYWOOD USED FOR THE BI-LEVEL SEPARATION.  THE CARDBOARD ALLOWED THE ALL READY TILTED DRUMS TO SETTLE, CAUSING AN ADDITIONAL OFF SET WHERE THE DRUMS DID NOT SET AN EVENLY SIDE BY SIDE.  A TOTAL OF 11 DRUMS WERE FOUND LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM CHIME, OR THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP, FROM ABRASION WITH ADJACENT DRUMS.  ESTIMATE 60 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST DURING TRANSPORTATION FORM THE 11 LEAKING DRUMS.  ALL THE LEAKING DRUMS WERE PATCHED AND PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR SECUREMENT.  44 ADDITIONAL DRUMS SUSTAINED SUFFICIENT DAMAGE TO WARRANT THEM UNFIT FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS.  THE SHIPPER REQUESTED THE ENTIRE LOAD BE RETURNED TO THE ORIGIN FACILITY.  A SECOND CONTAINER, PRSU 403079, WAS USED TO RELOAD ALL OF THE DAMAGED DRUMS. THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE PLACED BECK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER AND PROPERLY SECURED FOR MOVEMENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: THE FOLLOWING ARE THE EVENTS THAT LED UP TO THE ACCIDENT INVOLVING DAN STEWART, THE DRIVER OF A NORTH AMERICA COMPOSITES TRACTOR/TRAILER, ON SATURDAY 11/23/02, THAT OCCURRED AT MILE MARKER 34 ON I-81 IN TENNESSEE. ON THURSDAY 11/21/2002 AT APPROXIMATELY 5:00 P.M., THE DRIVER CALLED OUR DISTRICT MANAGER, DON LOCKRIDGE. MR. STEWART REPORTED THAT HE WAS DONE FOR THE DAY. HE ALSO LISTED HIS DELIVERIES FOR THE FOLLOWING DAY. LATER THAT SAME DAY, AT APPROXIMATELY 6:00 P.M., THE DRIVER'S WIFE TALKED TO HIM ON HIS CELL PHONE. MR. STEWART TOLD HER THAT HE WAS VERY NAUSEOUS. HE SAID HE WAS GOING TO FIND A HOTEL AND CALL HER WHEN HE ARRIVED. SHE ATTEMPTED TO REACH HER HUSBAND AGAIN AT 7:00 P.M. BUT HE DID NOT ANSWER HIS CELL PHONE. ON THE MORNING OF FRIDAY 11/22/2002, THE DRIVER'S WIFE CALLED DON LOCKRIDGE, DISTRICT MANAGER, AND REPORTED HER CONCERNS. MR. LOCKRIDGE CALLED THE CUSTOMERS TO FIND OUT IF THEE HAD BEEN ANY DELIVERIES THAT DAY (THERE HAD NOT BEEN ANY). HE THEN CALLED THE LAST CUSTOMER DELIVERED THE DAY BEFORE. THAT CUSTOMER REPORTED THAT THE DRIVER HAD GOTTEN EXTREMELY SICK (VOMITING) DURING THE DELIVERY. THEY OFFER TO HELP HIM BUT HE TOLD THEM HE WOULD GO TO A HOTEL. DURING THAT FRIDAY MORNING, DON LOCKRIDGE AND THE DRIVER'S WIFE EACH MADE NUMEROUS ATTEMPTS TO REACH MR. STEWART ON THE CELL PHONE WITH NO SUCCESS. THE REMAINING DELIVERY CUSTOMERS WERE MONITORED AS WELL, BUT MR. STEWART DID NOT SHOW AT ANY OF THESE LOCATIONS. ON THE AFTERNOON OF FRIDAY 11/22/2002, MR. LOCKRIDGE CALLED THE JOHNSON CITY POLICE DEPARTMENT (OFFICER PETERS) AND THE TENNESSEE HIGHWAY PATROL AT FALL BRANCH (OFFICER BENNETT) AND NOTIFIED THEM OF THE MISSING DRIVER. LATE FRIDAY NIGHT, OFFICER PETTERS CALLED TO INFORM MR. LOCKRIDGE THAT THEY HAD CHECKED EVERYWHERE IN JOHNSON CITY THAT THEY THOUGHT MR. STEWART COULD BE BUT THEY HAD BEEN UNABLE TO LOCATE HIM. AN ALL-POINTS-BULLETIN (APB) WAS ISSUED. ON THE MORNING OF SATURDAY 11/23/2002 AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 A.M., A STATE TROOPER FOUND MR. STEWART'S TRUCK PARKED IN THE MIDDLE OF HIGHWAY 66. HE CALLED A BACKUP OFFICER. THE TWO OFFICERS NOTICED THAT MR. STEWART'S SPEECH WAS SLURRED AND THAT HE WAS ACTING INCOHERENT AT TIMES. THEY RULED OUT DRUGS AND ALCOHOL. ALTHOUGH THERE WERE SUBSEQUENT INDICATORS THAT MR. STEWART MAY HAVE SUFFERED A SERIES OF STROKES SINCE HIS LAST DELIVERY, AT THE TIME THE OFFICERS SAW HIM, THEY CONCLUDED THAT MR. STEWART WAS SIMPLY SUFFERING FROM EXHAUSTION. THEY ESCORTED HIM TO A NEARBY TRUCK STOP AND TOLD HIM TO GET SOME SLEEP. THE OFFICERS GOT A DRIVER FROM ROADWAY, WHICH WAS NEARBY, TO DRIVE THE DAN STEWART'S VEHICLE TO THE TRUCK STOP. AT APPROXIMATELY 4:00 A.M. THAT SATURDAY, MR. STEWART TOOK HIS VEHICLE, LEFT THE GREENVILLE, TN TRUCK STOP AT EXIT # 23 ON I-81, AND HEADED NORTH. TWO TRUCKERS FOLLOWED HIM OUT OF THE TRUCK STOP AND NOTICED THAT HE WAS SWERVING ALL OVER THE INTERSTATE. THE TWO TRUCKS FOLLOWED OUR VEHICLE FOR 11 MILES (NEAR MILE MARKER 34). MR. STEWART'S TRUCK THEN VEERED OFF THE ROAD TO

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 10:12AM THE W/B ON THE FORWARD CRANE, MR. TOM STOICICH, REG# 8738, NOTICED A CONTAINER LEAKING FLUID, CAXU 9681847, LOADED IN LA, CODED DG, CARRYING RESIN SOLUTION WHICH IS FLAMMABLE.  ALL PRECAUTIONS WERE TAKEN, WORK WAS STOPPED TILL FURTHER NOTIFICATION FROM THE SHIPPER, ED HUGHLETT AS WELL THE COAST GUARD.  FOSS (ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES COMPANY) SHOWED UP AND AFTER INSPECTION BOTH THE COAST GUARD AND FOSS DECIDED THAT IT WOULD BE SAFE TO DISCHARGE THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS DISCHARGED TO THE DOCK AND A DIAPER WAS PUT AROUND THE LEAKING PART OF THE CONTAINER. IT WAS THEN TAKEN TO A ISOLATED SPOT IN THE YARD AND INSPECTED FURTHER. UPON OPENING THE DOORS TO THE CONTAINER IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS NO IMMEDIATE HAZARD AND SO FOSS CLOSED IT BACK UP AND TOOK IT TO THEIR YARD TO DE-VAN IT AND FIND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  THE PORT CAPTAIN WAS CONTACTED AND HE AUTHORIZED THE ENTIRE OPERATION TO TAKE PLACE.  OPERATIONS CONTINUED AT 14:12

FREIGHT SHIFTED DURING TRANSIT AND PUNCTURED ONE OF THE DRUMS.  DRIVER DETECTED MERCAPTAN ODOR NEAR THE REAR OF THE VEHICLE AND CONTACTED HIS DISPATCHER.  TRANSPORTER'S DISPATCHER AND OPERATIONS MANAGER CONTACTED:  1) THE NATIONAL SPILL CENTER AT 800-424-8802, 2) THE USEPA, AIR QUALITY AT 212-637-4249 - REPORT # 628737, 3) WILSON BOROUGH FIRE DEPARTMENT, 4) UGI (A LOCAL GAS COMPANY) AND A SPILL REMEDIATION FIRM.  MATERIAL RESOURCE RECOVERY (MRR) CONTAINED THE LEAKING DRUM, CLEANED UP ANY OF ITS SPILLED CONTENTS, AND PREPARED THE REMAINING PART OF THE SHIPMENT FOR DISPOSAL AT THEIR SITE LOCATED AT 2425 INDUSTRIAL PARK DRIVE, CORNWALL, ON, K6H5R5. UPON REMEDIATING THE SPILL, THE VEHICLE WAS TAKEN TO THEIR SITE FOR FINAL CLEANING (STEAM/TREATMENT).  THERE WERE NO NOTICEABLE ODORS COMING FROM THE VEHICLE AFTER THE SPILL WAS REMEDIATED.
